PiperOrigin-RevId: 397252444
Change-Id: Ieff05360969026d211759d5687fad6d179bee64b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/indhub/tensorflow/commits/8894bcd76e8ba0e6c26553b118fff169dd5f8126"},{"sha":"3e8a7c649efeaf99cbd2726d48fe857562d4720f","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"[retry]Fix a shape mismatch when partial batch handling is enabled

Partial batch handling will make the batch dimension unknown because of the
tf.cond(has_value, true_fn=get_value, false_fn=make_dummy). This tf.cond is
executed in DistributedIterator.get_next_as_optional() even when partial batch
handling is disabled. To counter this unnecessary shape lost, we recover the shape after tf.cond with the shape of the true branch. However we may recover it with the wrong shape when partial batch handling is enabled (as we could take the false branch).

This change refactors the partial batch handling logic so that
DistributedIterator.get_next() and DistributedIterator.get_next_as_optional()
is consistent.

The previous _get_next_as_optional is a misleading name as it does parial batch
handling and doesn't produce optional values. Hope that the picture is more
clear after this change.

tf.cond(has_value, true_fn=get_value, false_fn=make_dummy). This tf.cond is
executed in DistributedIterator.get_next_as_optional() even when partial batch
handling is disabled. To counter this unnecessary shape lost, we recover the shape after tf.cond with the shape of the true branch. However we may recover it with the wrong shape when partial batch handling is enabled (as we could take the false branch).

This change refactors the partial batch handling logic so that
DistributedIterator.get_next() and DistributedIterator.get_next_as_optional()
is consistent.

The previous _get_next_as_optional is a misleading name as it does parial batch
handling and doesn't produce optional values. Hope that the picture is more
clear after this change.

launch the ops (currently convolution and fused convolution), without exposing
the details of that data in the backend-independent interface.  In particular
this is for cuDNN `ExecutionPlans`, but in principle it could be used for any
cached compiled kernels, allocated descriptor objects, etc.

This PR tries to address the issue raised in 51936 where
max_pool3d will crash when any dim of ksize is 0 or negative.

While the original issue was raised toward tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling3D,
the issue can also be triggered when max_pool3d is called directly
with tensorflow itself.

For that reason a separate fix inside tensorflow is also fixed here.

This PR tries to address the issue raised in 51936 where
max_pool3d will crash when any dim of ksize is 0 or negative.

While the original issue was raised toward tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling3D,
the issue can also be triggered when max_pool3d is called directly
with tensorflow itself.

For that reason a separate fix inside tensorflow is also fixed here.

This PR fixes 51936.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Support different input, bias, and output types for fused convolutions.

XLA's convolution integration expects to be able to specify the three types
independently, but the initial cuDNN frontend TensorFlow support expected to
decide them internally.

A note on naming: when only one scalar type is involved, we call it
`element_type`: it's the type of the elements of all the relevant tensors.
When we have separate types for different tensors, we'll avoid using
`element_type` at all, and name types according to the particular tensor
they're related to.
